# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: web-accessibility
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-aria] Accessible Rich Internet Applications **(ARIA)** is a set of roles and attributes that define ways to make web content and web applications (especially those developed with JavaScript) more accessible to people with disabilities.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-aria] ARIA supplements HTML so that interactions and widgets commonly used in applications can be passed to assistive technologies when there is not otherwise a mechanism.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-aria] For example, ARIA enables accessible JavaScript widgets, form hints and error messages, live content updates, and more.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-aria] This progress bar is built using a `<div>`, which has no meaning.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-aria] We include ARIA roles and properties to add meaning.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-aria] In this example, the `role="progressbar"` attribute informs the browser that this element is actually a JavaScript-powered progress bar widget.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-aria] The `aria-valuemin` and `aria-valuemax` attributes specify the minimum and maximum values for the progress bar, and the `aria-valuenow` describes the current state of it and therefore must be kept updated with JavaScript.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-aria] All content that is available to non-assistive technology users must be made available to assistive technologies.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-aria] Similarly, no features should be included targeting assistive technology users that aren't also accessible to those not using assistive technologies.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-aria] The above progressbar needs to be styled to make it look like a progressbar.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-aria] Like any other web technology, there are varying degrees of support for ARIA.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-aria] Support is based on the operating system and browser being used, as well as the kind of assistive technology interfacing with it.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-aria] In addition, the version of the operating system, browser, and assistive technology are contributing factors.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-aria] Older software versions may not support certain ARIA roles, have only partial support, or misreport its functionality.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-aria] It is also important to acknowledge that some people who rely on assistive technology are reluctant to upgrade their software, for fear of losing the ability to interact with their computer and browser.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-aria] Because of this, it is important to use semantic HTML elements whenever possible, as semantic HTML has far better support for assistive technology.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-aria] It is also important to test your authored ARIA with actual assistive technology.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-aria] This is because browser emulators and simulators are not really effective for testing full support.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-aria] Similarly, proxy assistive technology solutions are not sufficient to fully guarantee functionality.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-aria] The ARIA reference is a comprehensive list of ARIA attributes and roles that are documented on MDN.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-aria] ARIA roles can be used to describe elements that don't natively exist in HTML or those which exist but don't yet have wide browser support.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-aria] ARIA attributes enable modifying an element's states and properties as defined in the accessibility tree.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-aria] The ARIA guides are resources that help you improve the accessibility of web page features such as tables, forms, and keyboard-navigation.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-aria] The official best practices documents how best to ARIA-ify common widgets and interactions.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-aria] Built-in elements like `<input>`, `<button>`, etc. have built-in keyboard accessibility.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-aria] If you 'fake' these with `<div>`s and ARIA, you must ensure your widgets are keyboard accessible.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-aria] Live regions provide suggestions to screen readers about how to handle changes to the contents of a page.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-intro] The Web is fundamentally designed to work for all people, whatever their hardware, software, language, location, or ability.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-intro] When the Web meets this goal, it is accessible to people with a diverse range of hearing, movement, sight, and cognitive ability.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-intro] Thus the impact of disability is radically changed on the Web because the Web removes barriers to communication and interaction that many people face in the physical world.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-intro] However, when websites, applications, technologies, or tools are badly designed, they can create barriers that exclude people from using the Web.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-intro] Web accessibility means that websites, tools, and technologies are designed and developed so that people with disabilities can use them.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-intro] The Web is an increasingly important resource in many aspects of life: education, employment, government, commerce, health care, recreation, and more.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-intro] It is essential that the Web be accessible in order to provide equal access and equal opportunity to people with diverse abilities.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-intro] Access to information and communications technologies, including the Web, is defined as a basic human right in the United Nations Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities (UN CRPD).
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-intro] The Web offers the possibility of unprecedented access to information and interaction for many people with disabilities.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-intro] That is, the accessibility barriers to print, audio, and visual media can be much more easily overcome through web technologies.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-intro] Web accessibility is **required by law** in many situations.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-intro] Web accessibility depends on several components working together, including web technologies, web browsers and other "user agents", authoring tools, and websites.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-intro] The W3C Web Accessibility Initiative (WAI) develops technical specifications, guidelines, techniques, and supporting resources that describe accessibility solutions.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-intro] These are considered international standards for web accessibility; for example, WCAG 2.2 is also an ISO standard: ISO/IEC 40500.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-intro] Many aspects of accessibility are fairly easy to understand and implement.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-intro] Some accessibility solutions are more complex and take more knowledge to implement.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-intro] It is most efficient and effective to incorporate accessibility from the very beginning of projects, so you don’t need go back and to re-do work.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-intro] When developing or redesigning a website, evaluate accessibility early and throughout the development process to identify accessibility problems early, when it is easier to address them.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-intro] Simple steps, such as changing settings in a browser, can help you evaluate some aspects of accessibility.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-intro] Comprehensive evaluation to determine if a website meets all accessibility guidelines takes more effort.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-intro] There are evaluation tools that help with evaluation.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-intro] However, no tool alone can determine if a site meets accessibility guidelines.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-intro] Knowledgeable human evaluation is required to determine if a site is accessible.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-intro] Images should include *equivalent alternative text* (alt text) in the markup/code.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-intro] If alt text isn’t provided for images, the image information is inaccessible, for example, to people who cannot see and use a screen reader that reads aloud the information on a page, including the alt text for the visual image.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-intro] When equivalent alt text is provided, the information is available to people who are blind, as well as to people who turn off images (for example, in areas with expensive or low bandwidth).
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-intro] It’s also available to technologies that cannot see images, such as search engines.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-intro] Some people cannot use a mouse, including many older users with limited fine motor control.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-intro] An accessible website does not rely on the mouse; it makes all functionality available from a keyboard.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-intro] Then people with disabilities can use assistive technologies that mimic the keyboard, such as speech input.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-intro] Just as images aren’t available to people who can’t see, audio files aren’t available to people who can’t hear.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-intro] Providing a text transcript makes the audio information accessible to people who are deaf or hard of hearing, as well as to search engines and other technologies that can’t hear.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-intro] It’s easy and relatively inexpensive for websites to provide transcripts.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-intro] There are also transcription services that create text transcripts in HTML format.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-intro] W3C WAI provides a wide range of resources on different aspects of web accessibility standards, education, testing/evaluation, project management, and policy.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility-intro] We encourage you to explore this website, or look through the WAI Resources list.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility] For many people, technology makes things easier.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility] For people with disabilities, technology makes things possible.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility] Accessibility means developing content to be as accessible as possible, no matter an individual's physical and cognitive abilities and how they access the web.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility] Our learn web development Accessibility module contains modern, up-to-date tutorials covering accessibility fundamentals.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility] This article starts off the module with a good look at what accessibility is — this includes what groups of people we need to consider and why, what tools different people use to interact with the web, and how we can make accessibility part of our web development workflow.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility] Next we turn our attention to accessibility tooling, providing information on the kinds of tools you can use to help solve accessibility issues, and the assistive technologies used by people with disabilities as they browse the web.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility] You'll be using these tools throughout subsequent articles.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility] A great deal of web content can be made accessible just by making sure the correct HTML elements are always used for the correct purpose.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility] This article looks in detail at how HTML can be used to ensure maximum accessibility.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility] CSS and JavaScript, when used properly, also have the potential to allow for accessible web experiences, but if misused they can significantly harm accessibility.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility] This article outlines some CSS and JavaScript best practices that should be considered to ensure that even complex content is as accessible as possible.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility] Following on from the previous article, sometimes making complex UI controls that involve unsemantic HTML and dynamic JavaScript-updated content can be difficult.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility] WAI-ARIA is a technology that can help with such problems by adding in further semantics that browsers and assistive technologies can recognize and use to let users know what is going on.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility] Here we'll show how to use it at a basic level to improve accessibility.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility] Another category of content that can create accessibility problems is multimedia — video, audio, and image content need to be given proper textual alternatives, so they can be understood by assistive technologies and their users.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility] With web access on mobile devices being so popular, and popular platforms such as iOS and Android having fully-fledged accessibility tools, it is important to consider the accessibility of your web content on these platforms.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility] This article looks at mobile-specific accessibility considerations.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility] The Accessibility guides cover authoring principles, WCAG compliance, accessible widgets and navigation, mobile accessibility, and other key topics that will help you understand why accessibility is crucial for the web and how to improve it in your projects.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility] This document lists guidelines and regulations, how-to's, and tools for checking and repairing accessibility problems with websites.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility] This article discusses making web content accessible for those with vestibular disorders, and those who support them, by taking advantage of personalization and accessibility settings built into the operating systems.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility] Most JavaScript libraries offer a library of client-side widgets that mimic the behavior of familiar desktop interfaces.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility] While this results in a widget that looks like its desktop counterpart, there usually isn't enough semantic information in the markup to be usable by an assistive technology.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility] This document describes techniques to improve accessibility of such widgets.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility] Until now, web developers who wanted to make their styled `<div>` and `<span>` based widgets accessible have lacked proper techniques.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility] **Keyboard accessibility** is part of the minimum accessibility requirements, which a developer should be aware of.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility] This document describes techniques to make JavaScript widgets accessible with the keyboard.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility] This document provides a concise checklist of accessibility requirements for mobile app developers.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility] A set of articles that provide quick explanations to help you understand the steps that need to be taken to conform to the recommendations outlined in the Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG).
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility] Cognitive accessibility covers accessibility considerations for people with cognition and learning disabilities.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility] This document introduces cognitive accessibility and improving accessibility of the web for people with cognitive and learning differences.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility] This document describes visual patterns that can induce physical symptoms in people who have photosensitive epilepsy, vestibular disorders, or other perceptual issues.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility] While understanding color, luminance, and saturation is important for design and readability for all sighted users, they are essential for those with reduced vision and color-deficient vision and those with specific neurological, cognitive, and other impairments.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility] Some types of visual web content can induce seizures in people with certain brain disorders.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility] This article helps you understand the types of content that can be problematic and find tools and strategies to help you avoid them.
[src:web-accessibility/accessibility] This is a collection of articles to learn how to use Accessible Rich Internet Applications (ARIA) to make your HTML documents more accessible.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] For example, when a site is coded with semantically meaningful HTML, with textual equivalents provided for images and with links named meaningfully, this helps blind users using text-to-speech software and/or text-to-Braille hardware.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] When text and images are large and/or enlargeable, it is easier for users with poor sight to read and understand the content.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] When links are underlined (or otherwise differentiated) as well as colored, this ensures that color blind users will be able to notice them.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] When clickable links and areas are large, this helps users who cannot control a mouse with precision.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] When pages are not coded in a way that hinders navigation by means of the keyboard alone, or a single switch access device alone, this helps users who cannot use a mouse or even a standard keyboard.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] When videos are closed captioned, chaptered, or a sign language version is available, deaf and hard-of-hearing users can understand the video.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] When flashing effects are avoided or made optional, users prone to seizures caused by these effects are not put at risk.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] Additionally, when content is written in plain language and illustrated with instructional diagrams and animations, users with dyslexia and learning difficulties are better able to understand the content.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] Accessibility considerations have increasingly been incorporated into website builders such as Wix, Duda, and Webnode, which offer tools to help create more accessible web content.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] When sites are correctly built and maintained, all of these users can be accommodated without decreasing the usability of the site for non-disabled users.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] Accessibility is not confined to the list above; rather, it extends to anyone who is experiencing any permanent, temporary or situational disability.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] Situational disability refers to someone who may be experiencing a boundary based on the current experience.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] For example, a person may be situationally one-handed if they are carrying a baby.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] Web accessibility should be mindful of users experiencing a wide variety of barriers.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] According to a 2018 WebAIM global survey of web accessibility practitioners, close to 93% of survey respondents received no formal schooling on web accessibility.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] In 1999 the Web Accessibility Initiative, a project by the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C), published the Web Content Accessibility Guidelines WCAG 1.0.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] On 11 December 2008, the WAI released the WCAG 2.0 as a Recommendation.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] WCAG 2.0 aims to be up to date and more technology neutral.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] Though web designers can choose either standard to follow, the WCAG 2.0 have been widely accepted as the definitive guidelines on how to create accessible websites.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] Governments are steadily adopting the WCAG 2.0 as the accessibility standard for their own websites.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] In 2012, the Web Content Accessibility Guidelines were also published as an ISO/IEC standard: "ISO/IEC 40500:2012: Information technology – W3C Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG) 2.0".
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] In 2018, the WAI released the WCAG 2.1 Recommendation that extends WCAG 2.0.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] There has been some criticism of the W3C process, claiming that it does not sufficiently put the user at the heart of the process.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] There was a formal objection to WCAG's original claim that WCAG 2.0 will address requirements for people with learning disabilities and cognitive limitations headed by Lisa Seeman and signed by 40 organizations and people.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] Because of the growth in internet usage and its growing importance in everyday life, countries around the world are addressing digital access issues through legislation.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] One approach is to protect access to websites for people with disabilities by using existing human or civil rights legislation.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] Some countries, like the U.S., protect access for people with disabilities through the technology procurement process.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] It is common for nations to support and adopt the Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG) 2.0 by referring to the guidelines in their legislation.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] Compliance with web accessibility guidelines is a legal requirement primarily in North America, Europe, parts of South America and parts of Asia.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] Law 26.653 on Accessibility to Information on Web Pages.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] Approved by the National Congress of Argentina on November 3, 2010.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] It specifies in its Article 1 that both the National State and its decentralized organisms or those companies that are related in any way with public services or goods, must respect the rules and requirements on accessibility in the design of their web pages.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] The objective is to facilitate access to contents to all persons with disabilities, in order to guarantee equal opportunities in relation to access to information and to avoid discrimination.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] In addition, by Decree 656/2019 the regulation of the aforementioned Law No.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] 26,653 is approved and it is reported that the authority in charge of its application will be the ONTI, "*Oficina Nacional de Tecnologías de Información*" (National Office of Information Technologies).
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] This agency is in charge of assisting and/or advising the individuals and legal entities reached by this Law; in addition to disseminating, approving/updating and also controlling the fulfillment of the accessibility standards and requirements of the web pages; among other functions.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] In 2000, an Australian blind man won a $20,000 court case against the Sydney Organising Committee of the Olympic Games (SOCOG).
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] This was the first successful case under Disability Discrimination Act 1992 because SOCOG had failed to make their official website, Sydney Olympic Games, adequately accessible to blind users.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] The Human Rights and Equal Opportunity Commission (HREOC) also published *World Wide Web Access: Disability Discrimination Act Advisory Notes*.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] All Governments in Australia also have policies and guidelines that require accessible public websites.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] In Brazil, the federal government published a paper with guidelines for accessibility on 18 January 2005, for public reviewing.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] On 14 December 2005, the second version was published, including suggestions made to the first version of the paper.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] On 7 May 2007, the accessibility guidelines of the paper became compulsory to all federal websites.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] The current version of the paper, which follows the WCAG 2.0 guidelines, is named ***e-MAG***, for ***Modelo de Acessibilidade de Governo Eletrônico*** (Electronic Government Accessibility Model), and is maintained by Brazilian Ministry of Planning, Budget, and Management.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] The paper can be viewed and downloaded at its official website.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] In 2011, the Government of Canada began phasing in the implementation of a new set of web standards that are aimed at ensuring government websites are accessible, usable, interoperable and optimized for mobile devices.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] These standards replace Common Look and Feel 2.0 (CLF 2.0) Standards for the Internet.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] The first of these four standards, *Standard on Web Accessibility* came into full effect on 31 July 2013.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] The Standard on Web Accessibility follows the Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG) 2.0 AA, and contains a list of exclusions that is updated annually.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] It is accompanied by an explicit Assessment Methodology that helps government departments comply.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] The government also developed the Web Experience Toolkit (WET), a set of reusable web components for building innovative websites.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] The WET helps government departments build innovative websites that are accessible, usable and interoperable and therefore comply with the government's standards.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] The WET toolkit is open source and available for anyone to use.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] The three related web standards are: the *Standard on Optimizing Websites and Applications for Mobile Devices*, the *Standard on Web Usability*, and the *Standard on Web Interoperability*.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] In 2019 the Government of Canada passed the Accessible Canada Act.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] This builds on the on provincial legislation like the Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act, The Accessibility for Manitobans Act and the Nova Scotia Accessibility Act.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] In February 2014, a draft law was endorsed by the European Parliament stating that all websites managed by public sector bodies have to be made accessible to everyone.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] A European Commission *Communication* on eAccessibility was published on 13 September 2005.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] The commission's aim to "harmonise and facilitate the public procurement of accessible ICT products and services" was embedded in a mandate issued to CEN, CENELEC and ETSI in December 2005, reference M 376.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] A mandate is a request for the drafting and adoption of a European standard or European standardisation deliverables issued to one or more of the European standardisation organisations.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] Mandates are usually accepted by the standardisation organisation because they are based on preliminary consultation, although technically the organisation is independent and has a right to decline the mandate.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] The mandate also called for the development of an electronic toolkit for public procurers enabling them to have access to the resulting harmonised requirements.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] The commission also noted that the harmonised outcome, while intended for public procurement purposes, might also be useful for procurement in the private sector.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] On 26 October 2016, the European Parliament approved the Web Accessibility Directive, which requires that the websites and mobile apps of public sector bodies be accessible.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] The relevant accessibility requirements are described in the European standard EN 301 549 V3.2.1 (published by ETSI).
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] Some categories of websites and apps are excepted from the directive, for example "websites and mobile applications of public service broadcasters and their subsidiaries".
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] The European Commission's "Rolling Plan for ICT Standardisation 2017" notes that ETSI standard EN 301 549 V1.1.2 will need to be updated to add accessibility requirements for mobile applications and evaluation methodologies to test compliance with the standard.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] In 2019 the European Union introduced the European Accessibility Act, as one of the leading pieces of legislation for digital accessibility and digital inclusion.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] The European Accessibility Act (EAA), which will enter into force on 28 June 2025, requiring companies to ensure that the newly marketed products and services covered by the Act are accessible.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] All websites will need to adhere to the WCAG Principles of Perceivable, Operable, Understandable and Robust, and deliver comparative levels of user experience to disabled customers.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] As of June 28, 2025, customers will be able to file complaints before national courts or authorities if services or products do not respect the new rules.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] In India, National Informatics Centre (NIC), under Ministry of Electronics and Information Technology (MeitY) has passed Guidelines for Indian Government Websites (GIGW) for government agencies in 2009, compelling them to adhere to WCAG 2.0 Level A standards.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] GIGW aims to ensure the quality and accessibility of government guidelines by offering guidance on desirable practices covering the entire lifecycle of websites, web portals and web applications, right from conceptualization and design to their development, maintenance and management.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] The Department of Administrative Reforms and Public Grievances made the same a part of the Central Secretariat Manual of Office Procedure.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] GIGW 3.0 also significantly enhances the guidance on the accessibility and usability of mobile apps, especially by offering specific guidance to government organizations on how to leverage public digital infrastructure devised for whole-of-government delivery of services, benefits and information.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] The Rights of Persons with Disabilities Act, 2016 (RPwD) passed in parliament.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] The law replaced earlier legislation and provided clearer guidance for digital accessibility.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] The RPwD Act, 106 through Sections 40-46 mandates accessibility to be ensured in all public-centric buildings, transportation systems, Information and Communication Technology (ICT) services, consumer products and all other services being provided by the Government or other service providers.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] In Ireland, the Disability Act 2005 requires that where a public body communicates in electronic form with one or more persons, the contents of the communication must be, as far as practicable, "accessible to persons with a visual impairment to whom adaptive technology is available" (Section 28(2)).
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] The National Disability Authority has produced a Code of Practice giving guidance to public bodies on how to meet the obligations of the Act.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] This is an approved code of practice and its provisions have the force of legally binding statutory obligations.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] In 2014, the Israeli Ministry of Justice published regulations requiring Internet websites to comply with Israeli standard 5568, which is based on the W3C Web Content Accessibility Guidelines 2.0.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] The main differences between the Israeli standard and the W3C standard concern the requirements to provide captions and texts for audio and video media.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] The Israeli standards are somewhat more lenient, reflecting the current technical difficulties in providing such captions and texts in Hebrew.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] In Italy, web accessibility is ruled by the so-called "Legge Stanca" (Stanca Act), formally Act n.4 of 9 January 2004, officially published on the Gazzetta Ufficiale on 17 January 2004.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] The original Stanca Act was based on the WCAG 1.0.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] On 20 March 2013 the standards required by the Stanca Act were updated to the WCAG 2.0.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] Web Content Accessibility Guidelines in Japan were established in 2004 as JIS (Japanese Industrial Standards) X 8341–3.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] JIS X 8341-3 was revised in 2010 as JIS X 8341-3:2010 to encompass WCAG 2.0, and it was revised in 2016 as JIS X 8341-3:2016 to be identical standards with the international standard ISO/IEC 40500:2012.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] The Japanese organization WAIC (Web Accessibility Infrastructure Committee) has published the history and structure of JIS X 8341-3:2016.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] In Malta Web Content Accessibility assessments were carried out by the Foundation for Information Technology Accessibility (FITA) since 2003.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] Until 2018, this was done in conformance with the requirements of the Equal Opportunities Act (2000) CAP 43 and applied WACG guidelines.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] With the advent of the EU Web Accessibility Directive the Malta Communications Authority was charged with ensuring the accessibility of online resources owned by Maltese public entities.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] FITA continues to provide ICT accessibility assessments to public and commercial entities, applying standard EN301549 and WCAG 2.1 as applicable.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] Therefore, both the Equal Opportunities Act anti-discrimination legislation and the transposed EU Web Accessibility Directive are applicable to the Maltese scenario.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] In Norway, web accessibility is a legal obligation under the Act 20 June 2008 No 42 relating to a prohibition against discrimination on the basis of disability, also known as the Anti-discrimination Accessibility Act.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] The regulations require compliance with Web Content Accessibility Guidelines 2.0 (WCAG 2.0) / NS / ISO / IEC 40500: 2012, level A and AA with some exceptions.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] The Norwegian Agency for Public Management and eGovernment (Difi) is responsible for overseeing that ICT solutions aimed at the general public are in compliance with the legislative and regulatory requirements.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] The Philippines was also the place where the Interregional Seminar and Regional Demonstration Workshop on Accessible Information and Communications Technologies (ICT) to Persons with Disabilities was held where eleven countries from the Asia-Pacific region were represented.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] The Manila Accessible Information and Communications Technologies Design Recommendations was drafted and adopted in 2003.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] In Spain, UNE 139803:2012 is the norm entrusted to regulate web accessibility.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] This standard is based on Web Content Accessibility Guidelines 2.0.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] In Sweden, Verva, the Swedish Administrative Development Agency is responsible for a set of guidelines for Swedish public sector web sites.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] Through the guidelines, web accessibility is presented as an integral part of the overall development process and not as a separate issue.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] The Swedish guidelines contain criteria which cover the entire life cycle of a website; from its conception to the publication of live web content.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] An English translation was released in April 2008: Swedish National Guidelines for Public Sector Websites.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] The translation is based on the latest version of Guidelines which was released in 2006.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] In the UK, the Equality Act 2010 does not refer explicitly to website accessibility, but makes it illegal to discriminate against people with disabilities.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] The Act applies to anyone providing a service; public, private and voluntary sectors.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] The *Code of Practice: Rights of Access – Goods, Facilities, Services and Premises* document published by the government's Equality and Human Rights Commission to accompany the Act does refer explicitly to websites as one of the "services to the public" which should be considered covered by the Act.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] In December 2010 the UK released the standard *BS 8878:2010 Web accessibility.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] This standard effectively supersedes PAS 78 (pub.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] PAS 78, produced by the Disability Rights Commission and usable by disabled people.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] The standard has been designed to introduce non-technical professionals to improved accessibility, usability and user experience for disabled and older people.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] It will be especially beneficial to anyone new to this subject as it gives guidance on process, rather than on technical and design issues.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] BS 8878 is consistent with the Equality Act 2010 and is referenced in the UK government's e-Accessibility Action Plan as the basis of updated advice on developing accessible online services.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] BS 8878 is intended for anyone responsible for the policies covering web product creation within their organization, and governance against those policies.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] It additionally assists people responsible for promoting and supporting equality and inclusion initiatives within organizations and people involved in the procurement, creation or training of web products and content.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] A summary of BS 8878 is available to help organisations better understand how the standard can help them embed accessibility and inclusive design in their business-as-usual processes.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] On 28 May 2019, BS 8878 was superseded by ISO 30071-1, the international Standard that built on BS 8878 and expanded it for international use.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] A summary of how ISO 30071-1 relates to BS 8878 is available to help organisations understand the new Standard.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] On April 9, National Rail replaced its blue and white aesthetic with a black and white theme, which was criticized for not conforming to the Web Content Accessibility Guidelines.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] The company restored the blue and white theme and said it is investing in modernising its website in accords to the latest accessibility guidelines.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] Statements should be published and linked to on every page on the website.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] Under the regulations, the Cabinet Office is required to monitor public sector compliance, with the work carried out by the Government Digital Service (GDS).
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] Between January 2022 and September 2024, GDS monitored 1,203 websites and 21 mobile applications, with 16,482 accessibility issues fixed as a direct result of the monitoring process.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] Enforcement is shared between the Minister for the Cabinet Office, the Equality and Human Rights Commission (EHRC) in Great Britain, and the Equality Commission for Northern Ireland (ECNI) in Northern Ireland, using powers under the Equality Act 2006 and the Disability Discrimination Act 1995.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] Of the 93 public sector bodies in England and Wales that the EHRC sent initial enforcement letters to between January 2022 and 2024, 66 secured compliance without further enforcement action.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] The European Accessibility Act (Directive (EU) 2019/882) entered into application on 28 June 2025, harmonising accessibility requirements for a range of digital products and services sold within the European Union, including e-commerce, banking, e-books, transport, and telecommunications.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] Although the United Kingdom left the European Union before the deadline, the directive continues to apply to UK businesses that supply covered products or services to EU consumers, irrespective of the supplier’s country of establishment.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] Microenterprises with fewer than 10 employees and an annual turnover below €2 million are exempt from some of the requirements.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] In the United States, Section 508 Amendment to the Rehabilitation Act of 1973 requires all Federal agencies' electronic and information technology to be accessible to those with disabilities.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] Both members of the public and federal employees have the right to access this technology, such as computer hardware and software, websites, phone systems, and copiers.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] Also, Section 504 of the Rehabilitation Act prohibits discrimination on the basis of disability for entities receiving federal funds and has been cited in multiple lawsuits against organizations such as hospitals that receive federal funds through medicare/medicaid.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] In addition, Title III of the Americans with Disabilities Act (ADA) prohibits discrimination on the basis of disability.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] There is some debate on the matter; multiple courts and the U.S.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] Department of Justice has endorsed the WCAG2.0AA standard as an appropriate standard for accessibility in multiple settlement agreements.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] Numerous lawsuits challenging websites and mobile apps on the basis of the ADA have been filed since 2017.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] These cases appears spurred by a 2017 case, *Gil v.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] Winn Dixie Stores*, in which a federal court in Florida ruled that Winn Dixie's website must be accessible.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] Around 800 cases related to web accessibility were filed in 2017, and over 2,200 were filed in 2018.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] Additionally, though the Justice Department had stated in 2010 that they would publish guidelines for web accessibility, they reversed this plan in 2017, also spurring legal action against inaccessible sites.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] A notable lawsuit related to the ADA was filed against Domino's Pizza by a blind user who could not use Domino's mobile app.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] At the federal district level, the court ruled in favor of Domino's as the Justice Department had not established the guidelines for accessibility, but this was appealed to the Ninth Circuit.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] The Ninth Circuit overruled the district court, ruling that because Domino's is a brick-and-mortar store, which must meet the ADA, and the mobile app an extension of their services, their app must also be compliant with the ADA.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] Domino's petitioned to the Supreme Court, backed by many other restaurants and retail chains, arguing that this decision impacts their Due Process since disabled customers have other, more accessible means to order.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] In October 2019, the Supreme Court declined to hear the case, which effectively upheld the decision of the 9th Circuit Court and requires the case to be heard as it stands.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] The number and cost of federal website accessibility lawsuits rose dramatically in 2018, climbing to a peak in 2022 before declining somewhat over the last couple years.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] A growing number of organizations, companies and consultants offer *website accessibility audits*.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] These audits, a type of system testing, identify accessibility problems that exist within a website, and provide advice and guidance on the steps that need to be taken to correct these problems.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] Ideally, a combination of methods should be used to assess the accessibility of a website.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] For a web page to be accessible all important semantics about the page's functionality must be available so that assistive technology can understand and process the content and adapt it for the user.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] However, as content becomes more and more complex, the standard HTML tags and attributes become inadequate in providing semantics reliably.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] Modern Web applications often apply scripts to elements to control their functionality and to enable them to act as a control or other dynamic component.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] These custom components or widgets do not provide a way to convey semantic information to the user agent.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] WAI-ARIA (Accessible Rich Internet Applications) is a specification published by the World Wide Web Consortium that specifies how to increase the accessibility of dynamic content and user interface components developed with Ajax, HTML, JavaScript and related technologies.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] ARIA enables accessibility by enabling the author to provide all the semantics to fully describe its supported behaviour.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] It also allows each element to expose its current states and properties and its relationships between other elements.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] Accessibility problems with the focus and tab index are also corrected.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] Automated accessibility testing tools have become a widely used first step in identifying accessibility barriers on websites.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] However, automated tools are capable of detecting only a portion of the accessibility issues present on a given page.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] Analysis of axe-core — the engine underlying tools such as Google Lighthouse — found that automated rules could be applied to approximately 16 out of 50 WCAG 2.1 Level AA success criteria, supporting industry estimates of 20–30% coverage when measured by criteria count.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] When measured by volume of real-world issues rather than criteria count, the same analysis found automated testing identified approximately 57% of issues found during full audits, as certain failure types occur with disproportionate frequency.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] Academic research evaluating multiple tools against identical content found that even running six automated tools in parallel left half of all WCAG 2 success criteria uncovered, with an estimated six in ten violations missed.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] A further independent analysis concluded that approximately 42% of WCAG success criteria cannot be detected through automated scanning at all, as they require human judgement about the quality, appropriateness, or usability of content.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] The W3C Web Accessibility Initiative states that "tools cannot check all accessibility aspects automatically" and that human judgement is required, noting that evaluation tools can sometimes produce false or misleading results.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] Most automated tools operate by inspecting the static structure of a web page — its HTML, ARIA attributes, and computed styles — without interacting with the page as a user would.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] This approach has inherent limitations in several areas.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] To address the limitations of static analysis, an approach has emerged that combines DOM inspection with programmatic browser automation.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] Tools built on frameworks such as Playwright or Puppeteer load a page in a real browser environment and simulate user interactions, enabling checks that static analysis cannot perform.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] Contemporary accessibility scanning tools vary significantly in which standards they evaluate against.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] In the United States, Section 508 Amendment to the Rehabilitation Act of 1973 requires federal agencies' electronic and information technology to be accessible, and was updated in 2017 to incorporate WCAG 2.0 Level AA by reference.
[src:web-accessibility/web-accessibility] In Europe, the standard EN 301 549, published by ETSI and referenced by the Web Accessibility Directive and the European Accessibility Act, incorporates WCAG criteria alongside additional requirements for non-web documents and software.
